##Refine the Scatterplot

Here we make the following updates:

Change the color to cyan, orange, blue so that color palette is categorical

Slightly modify the size of the points for readability

Modify the shape of the points to enhance ability to dicern size differences

Increase the font on the note indicating size is proportional to body mass in grams

Remove the penguin picture as this adds little to the overall chart

Change the title so that it gives context to the information displayed

Bill_length=penguin$bill_length_mm
Flipper_length=penguin$flipper_length_mm
species=penguin$species
peng_size=(penguin$body_mass_g/2500)

## identifying the species
Adelie.id = which(species=="Adelie")  # value are case sensitive!
Gentoo.id = which(species=="Gentoo")
Chinstrap.id = which(species=="Chinstrap")

## making an empty plot: type = "n" ==> no point
plot(Bill_length,Flipper_length,xlab = ("Bill Length in Millimeters"), ylab = ("Flipper Length in Millimeters"), main = "Comparison of Bill and Flipper Length by Penguin Species", type = "n")

points(Bill_length[Adelie.id], Flipper_length[Adelie.id], pch = 18, col = "cyan", cex=peng_size[Adelie.id])
points(Bill_length[Gentoo.id], Flipper_length[Gentoo.id], pch = 18, col = "blue", cex=peng_size[Gentoo.id])
points(Bill_length[Chinstrap.id], Flipper_length[Chinstrap.id], pch =18, col = "orange", cex=peng_size[Chinstrap.id])
legend("topleft", c( "Adelie", "Gentoo", "Chinstrap"), 
                  col=c("cyan", "blue", "orange"),
                  pch=c(18, 18, 18))

text(52, 173, "*The size of each point is proportional to body mass in grams", col = "black", cex = 0.75)

##Omit Missing Values

penguin<-na.omit(penguin)

##Subset as requested

penguin<- subset(penguin, (penguin$species == ("Adelie") | penguin$species == ("Gentoo")) & (3500<body_mass_g) & (body_mass_g<5000) & (penguin$island == ("Torgersen") | penguin$island == ("Biscoe")) , select=c(X1:year))

##Add a BMI Variable

penguin <- mutate(penguin,BMI=body_mass_g/4000)

penguin <- select(penguin,-c(X1,sex,year,body_mass_g))

##Paragraph comparing the relationship between the two variables across the species.

Based on the data we can see that Gentoo penguins from Torgersen and Biscoe with body mass between 3,500g and 5,000g tend to have both larger flipper length and larger bill length than Adelie penguins meeting the same criteria. We can also see that there appears to be more variation in the bill length of Adelie penguins than Gentoo penguins. The variation in flipper length seems to be about the same, with Adlei having perhaps slightly more variation. There are a few outliers, most notably the penguin at 44 x, 210 y with the largest flipper length and 4th largest bill length. This penguinn may warrant further investigation

Read in the life expectancy data from section 12

library (readr)

urlfile1="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsegich/STA553/main/data/income_per_person.csv"

urlfile2="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsegich/STA553/main/data/life_expectancy_years.csv"

urlfile3="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsegich/STA553/main/data/population_total.csv"

urlfile4="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jsegich/STA553/main/data/countries_total.csv"

income_per_person<-read_csv(url(urlfile1))

life_expectancy_years<-read_csv(url(urlfile2))

population_total<-read_csv(url(urlfile3))

countries_total<-read_csv(url(urlfile4))

##Prepare a single data set based on data set 12

income_per_person_fin <- income_per_person %>%
  gather(key = "Year",       # the column names of the wide table
         value = "Income",  # the numerical values of the table
         - geo,          # drop country variable: its value will not be gathered (stacked)!
         na.rm = FALSE)       # removing records with missing values

life_expectancy_years_fin <- life_expectancy_years %>%
  gather(key = "Year",       # the column names of the wide table
         value = "Life Expectancy",  # the numerical values of the table
         - geo,          # drop country variable: its value will not be gathered (stacked)!
         na.rm = FALSE)       # removing records with missing values

LifeExpIncom <- full_join(life_expectancy_years_fin,income_per_person_fin)

LifeExpIncom <- LifeExpIncom  %>%
                      mutate(year = substr(Year,1,5)) %>%
                      select(-Year)

innerjoin = merge(x = LifeExpIncom, y = countries_total, by.x = 'geo', by.y ='name', all = TRUE)

##Final data set 

Final_Set <- full_join(LifeExpIncom,innerjoin)
